    <div class="faq">
      <details class="qa">
        <summary>Are my documents private? <span class="plus">+</span></summary>
        <div class="a">Yes — this is the whole point of DocKit. Every tool runs entirely on your device, inside your browser. Your files are never uploaded to any server, there's no account, and DocKit even works offline. The only thing that ever touches the internet is a one-time license-key check when you activate Pro (which sends no file content).</div>
      </details>
      <details class="qa">
        <summary>What can DocKit do? <span class="plus">+</span></summary>
        <div class="a">DocKit is an all-in-one document suite: merge, split, rotate, reorder and compress PDFs; convert Word, Excel, CSV and images to and from PDF; fill forms and eSign; OCR scanned pages into searchable text; permanently redact sensitive content; add Bates numbering, headers and footers; and translate whole documents in place. Pro also runs any tool across a whole folder at once.</div>
      </details>
      <details class="qa">
        <summary>Is Pro really a one-time payment? <span class="plus">+</span></summary>
        <div class="a">Yes. DocKit Pro is a single payment of $19.99 (launch price) for lifetime access, including all future updates — no subscription, no recurring charges. You'll receive a license key by email to activate Pro instantly.</div>
      </details>
      <details class="qa">
        <summary>What's free and what's Pro? <span class="plus">+</span></summary>
        <div class="a">Every core tool is free on a single document — merging, converting, compressing, form-filling, and signing one page. Pro unlocks the professional tools (OCR, true redaction, Bates numbering) and everything that works at scale: batch processing across a folder, combining multiple files, full-document translation, and signing whole multi-page documents.</div>
      </details>
      <details class="qa">
        <summary>How does true redaction work? <span class="plus">+</span></summary>
        <div class="a">When you redact, DocKit doesn't just draw a black box over the text — that would leave the words selectable underneath, which is how real-world leaks happen. Instead, the redacted pages are flattened to an image with the black areas burned in, permanently destroying the underlying text and vectors. The rest of the document keeps its real, selectable text.</div>
      </details>
      <details class="qa">
        <summary>Which browsers are supported? <span class="plus">+</span></summary>
        <div class="a">DocKit works on Google Chrome and other Chromium-based browsers including Microsoft Edge, Brave, Opera and Vivaldi.</div>
      </details>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

